    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I saw a note in the manual about blockages being a serious issue though. What kind of things usually clog them up and how do pilots check if they've been compromised?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Pitot tubes can become clogged by ice during flight, freezing rain or snow, and sometimes debris like birds or bugs that are sucked in at high speed. Pilots perform a routine visual inspection of the tube and drain valves, often while the aircraft is on the ground, to ensure the ports are clear and the drain openings are unfrozen. If the airspeed indicator reads zero unexpectedly while aircraft is not flying, it is a telltale sign of a blockage that requires immediate investigation.",
